# Humanoid Robot Project

5-foot humanoid robot, 28-31 DOF target. Built from 2020 aluminum extrusion frame with PETG 3D-printed joint housings, driven by RobStride RS03 brushless actuators (60 N·m peak, 9:1 planetary, 48V nominal).

## Phases
- **Phase 1 (active):** Arms — 4 DOF per arm (shoulder pitch, shoulder roll, upper arm yaw, elbow pitch). Single arm wave demo is the first milestone.
- **Phase 2:** Legs — 6 DOF per leg (hip yaw/roll/pitch, knee pitch, ankle pitch/roll).
- **Phase 3:** Wrists & hands — 3+ DOF per side.
- **Phase 4:** Head — 2-3 DOF (neck pan/tilt, jaw/visor).

## Hardware Stack
- **Arm actuators:** RobStride RS03 (CAN ID 127 is the first motor, IDs TBD for rest)
- **Waist:** OpenQDD actuator
- **CAN adapters:**
  - Windows dev: RobStride CAN2USB debugger (CH340, COM5, 921600 baud)
  - Pi 5: Waveshare 2-CH Isolated CAN HAT (MCP2515 + SI65HVD230, SPI/SocketCAN)
- **Power:** 24V/1200W bench PSU (upgrading to 48V battery for mobile)
- **CAN buses:** Bus 0 (can0): Standard CAN 1 Mbps for RS03s. Bus 1 (can1): CAN-FD for Moteus (future)
- **Torso:** 460×200×160mm, 2020 extrusion with Mankk corner brackets
- **Onboard computer:** Raspberry Pi 5 (8GB), Ubuntu, hostname `robot.local`, user `joey`

## Software Stack
- **Language:** Rust (stable toolchain, MSVC on Windows, aarch64-linux on Pi)
- **Workspace:** Cargo workspace at repo root with two crates: `cortex` and `navi` (both have `socketcan` feature flag)
- **Key crate:** `robstride` (v0.3+, local patch at `robstride-local/`) — CH341Transport for CAN2USB, SocketCanTransport for Pi, RS03 protocol, async API
- **Runtime:** tokio (async, required by robstride Transport trait)
- **Config:** `serde` + `serde_yaml` for `config/robot.yaml`
- **`cortex/`** — motor control, arm coordination, config (the "brain stem")
  - `cortex/src/motor.rs` — high-level single-motor API (MIT-style control), joint limit enforcement, gravity-catch enable, fault code reading
  - `cortex/src/arm.rs` — multi-joint arm coordination, deterministic homing order, preflight checks, per-joint homing results
  - `cortex/src/config.rs` — typed config deserialization
  - `cortex/src/bin/probe.rs` — hardware probe / connectivity smoke test
  - `cortex/src/bin/motor_repl.rs` — interactive motor REPL for testing/tuning
  - `cortex/src/bin/wave_demo.rs` — arm wave demo (Phase 1 milestone)
- **`navi/`** — web server and telemetry (axum + WebTransport); pairs with `link/` frontend
  - `navi/src/main.rs` — `navi` binary entry point (`--config`, `--no-hardware`, `--port`, `--wt-port`)
  - `navi/src/api.rs` — REST API endpoints (motor CRUD, spin/torque/jog/stop/estop, arms, sequences, preflight, homing status, joint limit/home editing)
  - `navi/src/telemetry.rs` — motor polling + WebTransport datagram streaming (includes home/limit status per motor)
- **`link/`** — React frontend (Vite + TanStack Router + Tailwind)
  - Test Panel (`link/src/routes/test.tsx`) — motor jog/spin/torque/position/raw controls, sequence runner, global E-STOP
  - Arms page (`link/src/routes/arms.tsx`) — per-joint control, homing feedback, inline limit/home editor, preflight alerts
  - Overview (`link/src/routes/index.tsx`) — motor grid, homing status card, preflight violation banners
- Config lives in `config/robot.yaml` (transport: ch341 or socketcan)

## Homing & Joint Safety System
- **Three-layer limit enforcement:** UI slider constraints → API-level validation/rejection → Motor-level hard clamp on every command
- **Motor-level limits:** `Motor` struct stores `joint_limits: Option<(f32, f32)>`; `send_control()` clamps position; velocity/torque commands have soft boundary zone (linear ramp-down within ~10° of limits)
- **Gravity-catch:** `enable_with_hold(kp, kd)` enables motor and immediately holds current position to prevent gravity drop
- **Deterministic homing order:** `Arm` uses ordered `Vec` (YAML field order: shoulder_pitch first → elbow_pitch last); proximal-to-distal for safety
- **Pre-flight check:** `preflight_check()` reads all joint positions before enabling, blocks homing if any joint is outside limits (unless force override)
- **Per-joint homing results:** `StartupRecoverySummary` includes `Vec<JointHomingResult>` with status (AlreadyHome/Homed/StalledButHomed/TimedOut/Error/Skipped), timing, error magnitude
- **Runtime limit/home editing:** API endpoints persist changes to `robot.yaml` and update Motor instances live
- **Fault reading:** `read_fault_code()` reads raw 0x3022 register; `clear_faults()` sends StopCommand with clear_fault flag

## Link Frontend
- React 19, Vite, TypeScript, TanStack Router, Zustand, Recharts, Tailwind CSS 4
- "Link" is the primary interaction layer with the robot, not just a dashboard
- Pages: Overview, System, Arms, **Test** (motor controls + sequences), Settings, Logs
- Overview page includes: live Pi telemetry card, **HomingStatusCard** (per-arm homing status with colored indicators), **PreflightAlert** banners
- Arms page includes: per-joint control sliders with **limit proximity indicators** (amber near limit, red at limit), collapsible **joint config editor** (limits + home position + "Set Current as Home"), per-joint **homing result display**, preflight violation banners
- Dev: `cargo run -p navi --bin navi -- --no-hardware` for mock telemetry, `cd link && npm run dev` for HMR
- Production: `cd link && npm run build`, then `navi` binary serves from `link/dist/`

## Deployment
- **Windows dev:** COM5 for CAN2USB, `--no-hardware` for frontend-only dev
- **Pi 5 (robot.local):** Ubuntu, SocketCAN via Waveshare 2-CH CAN HAT, systemd services (`can-setup.service` + `link.service`), Rust 1.94.0 installed. Build with `cargo build --release --features socketcan`. SSH: `joey@robot.local` (key auth, NOPASSWD sudo)
- **HTTPS (Tailscale):** Enable MagicDNS + HTTPS Certificates in Tailscale admin DNS; on Pi run `deploy/renew-tailscale-cert.sh` → `certs/robot.pem` + `certs/robot-key.pem` for trusted TLS in the browser (`deploy/tailscale-https.md`). Re-run before ~90d expiry.
- **GitHub Actions CD:** On push to `main`, workflow runs CI checks, then deploys to Pi via self-hosted runner (`robot-local`), syncs repo to `~/mr_robot` (preserving `config/robot.yaml`), rebuilds (`socketcan` + frontend), installs `deploy/link.service` to systemd, and restarts `link.service`

## Key Decisions Already Made
- CAN2USB uses AT-framed serial: `'AT' [wire_id<<3|0x04, 4B BE] [len] [data] '\r\n'` at 921600 baud
- RS03 default CAN ID is 127 (not 1)
- Host CAN ID is 0xAA
- MotorStudio must be closed before the program can use COM5
- Written in Rust for performance, safety, and skill development
- The `robstride` Rust crate handles CH341 AT protocol and RS03 message construction natively
- **MIT-style control only** — RS03 firmware rejects RunMode parameter writes; use ControlCommand frames (comm_type 1) with kp/kd/position/velocity/torque packed in a single frame
- CAN2USB debugger DIP switch must be in position **2**
- REST for commands, WebTransport datagrams for real-time telemetry (no WebSockets)
- Telemetry snapshots now include host system metrics (`cpu_usage_percent`, `memory_used_mb`, `memory_total_mb`, optional `temperature_c`) sourced via `sysinfo`, plus per-motor `home_rad`, `home_error_rad`, `at_home`, and `limits`
- Frontend served from the robot itself (not cloud-hosted)
- Repo is a Cargo workspace — use `cortex::` for imports, not `robot::`
- Transport selection via `config/robot.yaml` `bus.transport` field: `"ch341"` (Windows) or `"socketcan"` (Pi)
- `navi` binary accepts `--config <path>` for deployment-specific config
- Waveshare CAN HAT interrupt pins: CAN_0=GPIO23, CAN_1=GPIO25 (verified from wiki, NOT GPIO25/24 as some docs say)
- **Joint limits are enforced at three layers** — Motor (hard clamp), API (informative reject), UI (visual constraints). Every code path (homing, API, REPL, wave demo) respects limits.
- **Homing is deterministic** — joints home in YAML field order (shoulder first, elbow last) with gravity-catch hold on each enable
- **Pre-flight check blocks homing** if any joint starts outside its limits (unless force override)
- **`startup_safe_recovery(force: bool)`** — the `force` parameter is required; pass `false` for normal use, `true` only for override
